<div class='allCommunityAnswers'>
<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/65586487-john-smith"><img alt="" src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/users/1488593692i/65586487._UY100_CR30,0,100,100_.jpg" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/65586487-john-smith">John Smith</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<span class="expandableContainer"><span class="truncatedContent">I&apos;ve read the book, you are sadly mistaken. <br/><br/>Sadly, because your parroting of Trump Derangement Syndrome, including a misspelling of his name in your c<a class="jsShow showAction" href="#">…more</a></span><span class="fullContent">I've read the book, you are sadly mistaken. <br /><br />Sadly, because your parroting of Trump Derangement Syndrome, including a misspelling of his name in your coinage (why would any adult bother with such juvenility?) is tiring and feckless. <br /><br />Mistaken, because the book covers leaders of any type, of corporations and nations, including A. Lincoln and Carly Fiorina, FDR and Chiang Kai-shek, The Shah of Iran and Saddam Hussein, and says they all have elements in common. In some ways Trump merits praise by the books standards, for instance he'd cut foreign aid, as suggested by De Mesquita.<br /><br />You should do some study and come to realize you own a poorly developed and strongly biased negative understanding of the man you think you are qualified to disparage. As such you fail in the effort.<a class="jsHide hideAction" href="#">(less)</a></span></span>
</span>
</div>
</div>
