    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1926585823" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1926585823" />
    <a title="Tom Stamper" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/24682440-tom-stamper"><img alt="Tom Stamper" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1471402186p2/24682440.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1926585823?book_show_action=true">Mar 05, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Tom Stamper" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Tom Stamper" href="/user/show/24682440-tom-stamper">Tom Stamper</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/24682440-tom-stamper?shelf=politics">politics</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1926585823" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17573781706192398080">This is maybe the most cynical book on politics that isn&apos;t trying to be humorous. According to the authors, the politics is driven by self-interest even when masked as compassion and empathy. What really happens is that political leaders build a coalition of supporters and as long as they pay off the supporters they stay in power. In a dictatorship it&apos;s easy because the coalition is small and the payoffs can be handsome. In a democracy it&apos;s more difficult because there are more mouths to feed so</span>
  <span id="freeText17573781706192398080" style="display:none">This is maybe the most cynical book on politics that isn't trying to be humorous. According to the authors, the politics is driven by self-interest even when masked as compassion and empathy. What really happens is that political leaders build a coalition of supporters and as long as they pay off the supporters they stay in power. In a dictatorship it's easy because the coalition is small and the payoffs can be handsome. In a democracy it's more difficult because there are more mouths to feed so the policy decisions have to be wider and the effects are smaller per person. <br /><br />From this starting point the authors explain predictable outcomes. For instance, democracies only fight wars they think they can win while dictatorships might actually be better off losing wars. The thinking here is that the cost of winning wars is so high that a dictator may not have any money left over to pay off his coalition. Winning the war might meaning losing power. In a Democracy the people expect the soldiers to have the best equipment and technology. The costs of such things divided over such a large coalition of voters is very small per person compared to the dictator's coalition.<br /><br />The last part of the book is the author's views on things that would improve politics. They have a very good idea on how to make foreign aid more effective. They propose putting the money into a Swiss bank escrow accounts to be released when countries reach certain objectives. The current system they argue rewards promises and not accomplishments because most countries know the aid will dry up once the goal is met. For instance, Pakistan had no real incentive to help us catch Bin Laden as long as we were paying them to help us catch him. Bin Laden would have been caught sooner had we just put a billion dollar price on his head.<br /><br />The one disagreement I had with their policy prescriptions is their promotion of open borders. While it's consistent with their hypothesis that larger coalitions of voters is better for the greater populace, it doesn't take into account the cultural divides that can negate those benefits. <br /><br />The book can be a bit much taken as a whole, but each lesson in itself makes a lot of intuitive sense. Politicians that aren't calculating aren't going to be in office long. Those who rise to the top have to be practical even if they have to fool themselves into thinking their decisions are altruistic. And even if the authors overstate a leader's lack of compassion when it comes to the citizenry, voters would be better served to see their leaders this way rather than be carried away by rhetoric and symbols of political campaigning. <br /><br />Being an idealist can make you feel better, but being a cynic can make you live longer. This book is a good framework in which to look at political decisions. It will make you ask yourself the kinds of questions that Meet the Press won't ask. It will help you get beyond the theater of politics and into the practical reasons politicians do what they do. </span>
  <a data-text-id="17573781706192398080" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

