    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2491540248" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2491540248" />
    <a title="Roslyn" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3745545-roslyn"><img alt="Roslyn" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/f_50x66-6a03a5c12233c941481992b82eea8d23.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2491540248?book_show_action=true">Aug 12, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Roslyn" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Roslyn" href="/user/show/3745545-roslyn">Roslyn</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2491540248" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8453207016907413141">I liked this book. But not as much as I liked the YouTube video. I don&apos;t think I really got anything out of the book that I didn&apos;t get out of the twenty minute video on this book, except examples, which I enjoyed, but that doesn&apos;t really change the fact that the book was far too long, repetitive, and not all that well-written. <br/><br/>I got the impression that the author was not sharing everything he knows, that the purpose of this book was to share enough to convince powerful people to hire him as an a</span>
  <span id="freeText8453207016907413141" style="display:none">I liked this book. But not as much as I liked the YouTube video. I don't think I really got anything out of the book that I didn't get out of the twenty minute video on this book, except examples, which I enjoyed, but that doesn't really change the fact that the book was far too long, repetitive, and not all that well-written. <br /><br />I got the impression that the author was not sharing everything he knows, that the purpose of this book was to share enough to convince powerful people to hire him as an advisor i.e. the purpose of this book is not to overly enlighten the reader. Like The Prince, this book is a job application.<br /><br />Also, Bruce sells democracy as the ideal (or least-bad) political system. But it seems to me that democracy is a different system that political actors must game, but it is no less game-able, it just requires more sophisticated levels of complexity. It's harder for those who live in democracies to realize they are little more than peasants being farmed... and yet that's what they are. And no, not for the senators, governors and presidents that Bruce writes are "those in power." <br /><br />Bruce writes that in democracies the leaders must kowtow to the little people or risk losing their positions. But I think most politicians are little more than tools working for those who are actually in power. The genius of the democratic political system is that the peasants can't rebel and kill their masters because they have no idea who they are. Also, how much do politicians in democracies really have to kowtow to their constituents? Seems to me that the tax cows in democracies are hit with nonstop propaganda and encouragement to entertain and drug themselves into oblivion - they barely pay attention to politics. And if they do, they just regurgitate whatever the media or the church of academia tell them to. <br /><br />And on that note: Bruce wants to keep his job as much as politicians want to keep theirs, and academia is the church of a democracy whose job is to sell the current political system to the people and validate the current power structures. Moreover, the political system that grants the most power and financial rewards to academics is democracy. So Bruce has everything to gain by selling democracy and not thinking outside that box at all.<br /><br />And yes, I am simplifying. Bruce had some good points, but I don't trust him or the "advice" he is willing to share openly with the masses for $20 at all.<br /><br />The YouTube video gets 5 stars.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8453207016907413141" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


